# File: tests/e2e/user-scrolls-grid-feed.spec.sh.ab
# Purpose: Verify infinite scroll works correctly in the 3-column grid — viewport-fill auto-load triggers when the grid compresses height, and manual scrolling loads more pages
# Dependencies: [app/app/pages/dashboard/desktop/dashboard.directive.js.ab, app/assets/scss/_feed-grid.scss.ab, app/app/post/post.directive.js.ab]

## Overview
An authenticated user loads the desktop listing feed in the 3-column grid. Because the grid compresses vertical height (3 cards per row instead of 1), the initial batch of cards may not make the page scrollable. The viewport-fill check must automatically load additional pages until the page is scrollable, then normal scroll-based pagination takes over as the user scrolls toward the bottom.

## Covers
app/app/pages/dashboard/desktop/dashboard.directive.js.ab, app/assets/scss/_feed-grid.scss.ab, app/app/post/post.directive.js.ab

## Business Actor
Authenticated user browsing the listing feed on a desktop browser, expecting continuous content loading without dead ends.

## Business Goal
Scroll through an endless listing feed without encountering a premature stop — the feed should keep loading pages whether triggered automatically (viewport fill) or by user scrolling.

## Test Accounts
<!-- Credentials are defined here and used verbatim by the translator. Do NOT read from .env or any external file. -->
<!-- Each actor gets a base email. At runtime the translator appends +<random_id> to make it unique per run. -->
- Actor `user`: base email `e2e.scrolluser@test.local`, password `Test1234!`

## Preconditions
- Each run creates a fresh isolated account using `e2e.scrolluser+<random_id>@test.local` via the registration API before Scenario A runs. This account is fully isolated — no shared state with other specs or runs.
- The test environment contains a sufficient number of donation listings (read-only seed data) such that multiple pages of results are available from the API.
- Desktop viewport is set to 1280x800 so that the initial 3-column batch may not fill the full viewport height.

Teardown (after all scenarios, even on failure):
- Delete the per-run account created during setup and all records it owns.
- Do NOT delete shared read-only seed fixtures.

## Business Scenarios
- Scenario A (DB-1): Feed loads and page is not scrollable — viewport-fill auto-loads next page
- Scenario B (DB-2): After viewport fill, user scrolls toward bottom and triggers normal infinite scroll
- Scenario C (DB-3): API returns empty results during auto-load — cycle terminates cleanly

## Actor Variants
- EQ-1 — First page renders in 3-column grid and document height does not exceed viewport -> viewport-fill auto-load triggers -> DB-1
- EQ-2 — First page renders and document height already exceeds viewport (page is scrollable) -> no auto-load needed, user scrolls normally -> DB-2
- EQ-3 — All available content exhausted during viewport-fill cycle (API returns empty before page becomes scrollable) -> DB-3

## Outcome Branches
- DB-1 -> Viewport-fill check triggers automatic next-page load; repeated until page is scrollable (EQ-1)
- DB-2 -> User scrolling toward bottom triggers further normal infinite-scroll loads (EQ-2)
- DB-3 -> API returns empty elements array during auto-load cycle; cycle terminates, feed stops loading, no silent loop (EQ-3)

## Business Boundaries
- BV-1 (document height exactly equals viewport height after first batch): auto-load should still trigger since the page is not scrollable
- BV-2 (document height 1px below viewport height): clearly below threshold, auto-load must trigger
- BV-3 (document height 1px above viewport height): above threshold, auto-load must NOT trigger again

## Acceptance Criteria
- AC1: When the 3-column grid compresses content height below the viewport, additional pages load automatically without the user scrolling (DB-1, EQ-1)
- AC2: After the page becomes scrollable (via viewport fill or sufficient initial content), scrolling toward the bottom triggers the next page load (DB-2, EQ-2)
- AC3: When the API returns an empty result set during auto-load, the cycle terminates cleanly and the feed shows all available content (DB-3, EQ-3)
- AC4: At the boundary where document height equals viewport height, auto-load still triggers (BV-1)
- AC5: When document height just barely exceeds viewport, auto-load does not trigger unnecessarily (BV-3)
- AC6: No further API calls are made after all content is loaded (ABSENT-1)
- AC7: No duplicate cards appear across batches during viewport-fill auto-load (ABSENT-2)
- AC8: The feed never silently stops at the first batch with whitespace below (ABSENT-3)

## Absent Elements
- After all content is loaded: no further API calls made (auto-load cycle terminates cleanly)
- During viewport-fill auto-load: no duplicate cards rendered across batches
- When feed has been loaded without user scrolling: feed does not silently stop at first batch with whitespace below

## Steps

### Scenario A: Viewport-fill auto-load triggers on short page
<!-- covers: DB-1, EQ-1, BV-1, BV-2, ABSENT-2, ABSENT-3 -->
1. Log in as the test user on a desktop viewport (1280x800)
2. Navigate to the listing feed at $E2E_BASE_URL
3. Wait for the initial batch of cards to render in the 3-column grid
4. Observe whether the page becomes scrollable after the first batch
5. If the page is not scrollable (first batch height < viewport), verify AC1: additional cards appear automatically without the user scrolling
6. Wait for the auto-load cycle to complete (page becomes scrollable or all content loads)
7. Verify AC8 (Absent): the feed is not stuck at the first batch with whitespace below the last card
8. Verify AC7 (Absent): no duplicate cards are visible — each listing appears exactly once
9. Count the total cards visible — should be more than the first batch if auto-load triggered
10. Take a screenshot and save to $E2E_ARTIFACTS_DIR/grid-scroll/viewport-fill-complete.png

### Scenario B: Normal infinite scroll after viewport fill
<!-- covers: DB-2, EQ-2, BV-3 -->
1. After Scenario A completes, the page should now be scrollable
2. Scroll toward the bottom of the feed (within 400px of the document bottom)
3. Verify AC2: a loading indicator appears and a new batch of cards loads
4. Verify the new cards append below the existing ones in the 3-column grid
5. Scroll to the bottom again to confirm infinite scroll continues working
6. Take a screenshot and save to $E2E_ARTIFACTS_DIR/grid-scroll/infinite-scroll-next-page.png

### Scenario C: API returns empty — auto-load terminates
<!-- covers: DB-3, EQ-3, ABSENT-1 -->
1. Continue scrolling through the feed until all available listings have been loaded
2. Verify AC3: the feed shows all available content and stops loading
3. Verify AC6 (Absent): no further loading indicators appear — the auto-load cycle has terminated
4. Scroll to the very bottom — no additional API requests trigger
5. Verify the feed displays a natural end state (no infinite spinner)
6. Take a screenshot and save to $E2E_ARTIFACTS_DIR/grid-scroll/all-content-loaded.png

